{"id":"2103.06337","submitter":"Xinping Shi","authors":"Kexin Liu, Xinping Shi, Frank Angeles, Ramya Mohan, Jon Gorchon,\n  Sinisa Coh, Richard B. Wilson","title":"Differentiating Contributions of Electrons and Phonons to the\n  Thermoreflectance Spectra of Gold","comments":"30 pages, 5 figures, 7 supplemental figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Materials 5, 106001(2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevMaterials.5.106001","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  To better understand the many effects of temperature on the optical\nproperties of metals, we experimentally and theoretically quantify the electron\nvs. phonon contributions to the thermoreflectance spectra of gold. We perform a\nseries of pump/probe measurements on nanoscale Pt/Au bilayers at wavelengths\nbetween 400 and 1000 nm. At all wavelengths, we find that changes in phonon\ntemperature, not electron temperature, are the primary contributor to the\nthermoreflectance of Au. The thermoreflectance is most sensitive to the\nelectron temperature at wavelength of ~480 nm due to interband transitions\nbetween d-states and the Fermi-level. In the near infrared, the electron\ntemperature is responsible for only ~2% of the total thermoreflectance. We also\ncompute the thermoreflectance spectra of Au from first principles. Our\ncalculations further confirm that phonon temperature dominates\nthermoreflectance of Au. Most of Au's thermoreflectance is due to the effect of\nthe phonon population on electron lifetime.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Mar 2021 20:40:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 4 Oct 2021 21:32:07 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 25 Oct 2021 16:35:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-26"}
